## User Review Required

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Frame rate & bandwidth tradeoff:** The browser will send ~1 frame per second at 480p JPEG quality. This keeps bandwidth low (~20-50KB per frame) while still catching violations in near-real-time. Is 1 FPS acceptable for proctoring accuracy?

> [!WARNING]
> **`winsound` module:** The current `proctor_live.py` imports `winsound` (Windows-only) at the top level. On Linux/Docker, this will crash the import. I will guard it with a `try/except` and make the buzzer a no-op on non-Windows platforms.

> [!NOTE]
> **Local dev is unchanged:** If you run locally, the old MJPEG flow (`/video_feed`) still works. The frontend-push is used *in addition to* the old mode — the ProctoringPanel now shows the native browser `<video>` element instead of the MJPEG `<img>`, and frames are pushed to the backend for analysis. The backend no longer needs to open `cv2.VideoCapture` — it just receives frames from the browser.

